	<p>Our users trust us to protect their identities and we take this responsibility seriously. We collect very little nonpublic information about users and retain that information for a short period of time.</p>

	<p>However, every year, law enforcement officials, government agencies, individuals, and corporations ask us to disclose users’ personal information. Often, we have no nonpublic information to disclose. But when we do, we carefully evaluate every request before considering disclosure. If the requests do not meet our standards -- if they are overly broad, unclear, or irrelevant -- we will push back on behalf of our users. You can also learn more about our efforts to reform US laws that set unclear legal standards about disclosure of user information in our FAQ.</p>

	<p>If we must comply with a legally valid request, we will notify the affected user before we disclose, if we are legally permitted and have the means to do so. In certain cases, we may provide financial assistance to users to fight an invalid request. </p>

